Research

Evolutionary fitness is maximized in different ways in males and females. For example, in many birds, males sing and have vibrant or ornamental feathers to attract females and get the opportunity to reproduce, but those traits come at a cost increased risk of being eaten because they are more conspicuous or less mobile. Females, because they are not having to attract mates with displays, can live much more inconspicuously thats why female birds are often relatively dull compared to their male counterparts.

But selection cannot drive males and females to look and behave differently with impunity selection affects which variants of genes are more likely to pass to the next generation, but the vast majority of genes present and expressed in both sexes. This means that variants, such as those producing longer more colorful tail feathers in males, will also have a similar effect in females. This creates an evolutionary conflict between the sexes over how the genome is optimized an evolutionary tug of war.

My work used quantitative genetic approaches those using intricate experimental designs, large datasets and advanced statistical methods to describe the genetic architecture of traits to understand

  • how pervasive intersexual genetic conflict is
  • how readily a genetic disconnect between the sexes can be generated
  • how genetic connections between the sexes are affected by genetic mutation and environmental change
  • whether sex chromosomes can play a special role in the evolution of sex differences.

Using gene expression data, covering many thousands of genes assayed in both sexes from 40 inbred-lines of fruit flies, I have shown that there is considerable potential for pervasive genetic constraint on the evolution of sex differences. By modifying the hemiclone method, I have shown that there are considerable differences between the X-chromosome and autosomes in the degree of genetic coupling between males and females for lifespan and ageing in fruit flies. Using church records, I have also shown that sex differences in male and female life expectancy in humans where women increasingly tend to outlive men may be explained by environmental change.

I consider myself fortunate to have had the chance to pursue a career in academia for the years that I chose to do so. It took me all over the world, gave me the opportunity to present and discuss work at major conferences and collaborate with some of the best researchers in my field. Above all, it gave me the freedom to let experiments and data lead the way, with results both answering and generating questions. Ultimately I left academia due to the costs it imposed on my family life and well-being.

My articles can be find through Google scholar, while my PhD thesis can be found here. While my career is no longer in academia, I am still actively collaborating and open to further collaborations, where I can contribute with the conception, planning, analysis and publication of research experiments.
